<xh:h3 xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">Rings</xh:h3>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
<col_ol environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ol">
<col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Definition</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Division Theorem</xh:b> for $\mathbb{Z}$ and $k[x]$ ($k$ a field).
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">GCD</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Euclidean Algorithm</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">B&amp;eacute;zout's Identity</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Chinese Remainder Theorem</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Integral Domains</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Fields</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Field of Fractions</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Ring homomorphism</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Isomorphism</xh:b>, <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Kernel</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Ideals</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Quotient Rings</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">First Isomorphism Theorem</xh:b>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Example</xh:b>
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
$a, b \in \mathbb{Z}$, $gcd(a, b) = 1$.  Then:
\[
\mathbb{Z}/(ab) \cong \mathbb{Z}/(a) \times \mathbb{Z}/(b)
\]
</newcol>
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ol" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ol">Example</xh:b>
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Let $I, J$ be ideals of a commutative ring $R$, such that:
\[
R = I + J := \{i + j : i\in I, j \in J\} 
\]
Then,
\[
R/(I \cap J) \cong R/I \times R/J.
\]
</newcol>
</col_li></col_ol>
